---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-nigeria', text: 'Leaving Nigerian Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'currency-matters', text: 'Currency Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best Africa Insurance', href: '/best/africa-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best UK Expat Insurance', href: '/best/uk-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'usNetwork', header: 'US Network' },
  { key: 'ukNetwork', header: 'UK Network' },
  { key: 'nigeriaCoverage', header: 'Nigeria Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', usNetwork: 'Strong', ukNetwork: 'Strong', nigeriaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', usNetwork: 'Excellent', ukNetwork: 'Excellent', nigeriaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', usNetwork: 'Good', ukNetwork: 'Strong', nigeriaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$175/mo' },
  { provider: 'AXA Global', usNetwork: 'Good', ukNetwork: 'Strong', nigeriaCoverage: 'Included', price: '$190/mo' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', usNetwork: 'Good', ukNetwork: 'Good', nigeriaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$150/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Nigerian Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Nigerian expats. Find coverage for the US, UK, Canada, and other destinations."
  headline="Best Insurance for Nigerian Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Nigerians abroad form one of Africa's largest diaspora populations. Here's how to stay protected in the US, UK, Canada, and beyond."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/nigerian-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Nigerian expats are concentrated in the US, UK, Canada, and increasingly the UAE. Healthcare costs in these destinations—especially the US—make comprehensive insurance essential. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Nigerian expats. Strong US and UK networks, comprehensive coverage, reliable service.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent networks in the US and UK. Top-tier service quality.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong UK network.</li>
    <li><strong>AXA Global:</strong> Good coverage with Nigeria included. Strong European networks.</li>
    <li><strong>IMG Global:</strong> Budget-friendly option with adequate global coverage.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="US Healthcare Costs"
    description="If you're moving to the United States, healthcare costs there are extreme. A single hospital stay can cost $50,000-$200,000+. Comprehensive insurance isn't optional—it's essential for financial survival."
    buttonText="Get US Coverage Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-nigeria">Leaving Nigerian Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Nigeria's healthcare system includes the NHIS and private HMOs. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>NHIS (National Health Insurance Scheme)</h3>
  <p>
    NHIS coverage is linked to Nigerian employment in the formal sector. When you leave Nigeria, this coverage ends. There's no international extension of NHIS benefits.
  </p>

  <h3>Private HMOs</h3>
  <p>
    Nigerian HMOs (Leadway, Hygeia, AXA Mansard, etc.) provide coverage within Nigeria. International coverage is typically limited to 30-90 days of emergency treatment abroad. For long-term stays overseas, you need dedicated international insurance.
  </p>

  <h3>Medical Tourism Consideration</h3>
  <p>
    Many Nigerians travel abroad for medical treatment. International insurance policies often cover treatment anywhere in their coverage area—so you could potentially receive care in the UK or India while covered by your policy, depending on plan terms.
  </p>

  <h2 id="currency-matters">Currency Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Currency is a significant consideration for Nigerian expats:
  </p>

  <h3>Naira Volatility</h3>
  <p>
    The Nigerian naira has experienced significant volatility. USD or EUR-denominated policies provide stability—your coverage maintains its value regardless of naira movements.
  </p>

  <h3>Payment Methods</h3>
  <p>
    International insurers accept various payment methods:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>International credit/debit cards (Visa, Mastercard)</li>
    <li>Wire transfers from foreign bank accounts</li>
    <li>Payment from your income in your destination country</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Premium Affordability</h3>
  <p>
    International insurance costs $150-300/month—significant in naira terms, but essential in destinations like the US or UK. Consider this a non-negotiable expense for financial protection.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">The Cost Reality</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      International insurance may seem expensive, but one medical emergency in the US without coverage can result in bills exceeding $100,000. The monthly premium is small compared to potential catastrophic costs.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage ideal for Nigerian expats. Strong networks in the US and UK—the two most popular Nigerian expat destinations. Three coverage tiers with limits up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    24/7 English service, direct billing at major hospitals worldwide. Nigeria coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Nigerian expats who want reliable global coverage, especially in the US or UK.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent US and UK networks. Service quality is outstanding, and plans are comprehensive including mental health and maternity.
  </p>

  <p>
    Higher pricing reflects premium positioning. Best for professionals who can afford top-tier coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Nigerian professionals who want the best coverage available.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong UK network makes this suitable for Nigerian expats in Britain. European networks are also excellent.
  </p>

  <p>
    Good value for comprehensive coverage without the highest premium prices.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Nigerian expats seeking good value, especially for UK or European destinations.
  </p>

  <h3>AXA Global</h3>
  <p>
    AXA has presence in Nigeria (AXA Mansard) and globally. Their international products include Nigeria coverage automatically, useful for those visiting home regularly.
  </p>

  <p>
    Strong European networks, adequate US coverage. Good option for those who want seamless Nigeria coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Nigerian expats who visit home frequently and want included Nigeria coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>IMG Global</h3>
  <p>
    IMG Global offers budget-friendly international coverage. Networks and service may not match Cigna or Bupa, but pricing is significantly lower. Good option for younger expats watching costs.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Budget-conscious Nigerian expats who need adequate coverage at lower prices.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Your Options"
    description="Get quotes from multiple providers to find the best balance of network strength, coverage, and price for your destination."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs vary by destination. Here's what Nigerian expats should consider:
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    The US has the most expensive healthcare in the world. Texas, Georgia, New York, and California have large Nigerian communities. Direct billing and strong US networks are essential—a hospital stay without coverage can be financially devastating.
  </p>

  <h3>United Kingdom</h3>
  <p>
    NHS provides free healthcare to legal residents with proper visa status. Many Nigerian expats supplement NHS with private insurance for faster access. London has extensive Nigerian community healthcare networks.
  </p>

  <h3>Canada</h3>
  <p>
    Provincial healthcare is available to permanent residents after a waiting period (typically 3 months). International insurance covers this gap. Toronto, Calgary, and Ottawa have significant Nigerian populations.
  </p>

  <h3>United Arab Emirates</h3>
  <p>
    Health insurance is mandatory in the UAE. Many employers provide coverage. Dubai and Abu Dhabi have growing Nigerian expat communities and good healthcare facilities.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does NHIS cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. NHIS only covers care in Nigeria. You need dedicated international health insurance for coverage while living abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep my Nigerian HMO abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Nigerian HMOs provide very limited international coverage (usually 30-90 days emergency only). For long-term stays, you need proper international insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is US health insurance really that expensive?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. A single hospital stay in the US can cost $50,000-$200,000+. International insurance at $150-250/month is far cheaper than US domestic insurance and protects against catastrophic bills.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">How do I pay from Nigeria?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Use international cards, wire transfers, or pay from your foreign income. Some Nigerian cards work internationally; check with your bank about foreign transaction capabilities.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage during Nigeria visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most international insurers offer Nigeria as a coverage region. AXA includes it automatically. Confirm details with your chosen provider.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Nigerian doctors abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes, especially in the UK and US cities with large Nigerian populations. Your insurer covers any qualified doctor—but Nigerian community networks can help find culturally familiar providers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Nigerian expats need comprehensive international insurance—Nigerian healthcare coverage doesn't extend abroad. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for reliable coverage in the US and UK. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those who can afford the best.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Allianz Care</strong> provides good value for UK and European destinations. <strong>AXA Global</strong> suits those who visit Nigeria frequently. <strong>IMG Global</strong> offers budget-friendly options.
  </p>

  <p>
    Don't underestimate US healthcare costs—they can be financially devastating without insurance. The monthly premium is a small price for peace of mind and financial protection.
  </p>

</PageShell>
